1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
This is Pam.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Oh my God, are you sure?

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:10,000
Okay, okay, we'll be right there.

4
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:14,000
Everybody, the balloon is falling!

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:19,000
There's this balloon that has been floating in the rafters of the warehouse for like, ever.

6
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:23,000
And, okay, it doesn't sound cool, you just have to see it.

7
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Well, I guess it doesn't look that cool either.

8
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:34,000
But, it's been up there a long time, so it's become a pretty big deal.

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Wow. It's the end of an era.

10
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:41,000
You did a good job, buddy. Now it's time to come home.

11
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:45,000
I remember when that balloon went up there. I was still with Gil.

12
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:47,000
We were so happy.

13
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:51,000
When that went up there, I had hair like Rapunzel.

14
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:55,000
How long do you think it's been up there, Kevin?

15
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:02,000
I just remember pushing aside my silky bangs to say, look, a balloon.

16
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
My Warcraft clan was still on speaking terms.

17
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
My kid didn't have a face tattoo.

18
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
I was still thinking of going back to school.

19
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:12,000
And I was still just a paper salesman.

20
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Well, this has been fun, Pam. Thanks for calling us all down here.

21
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Kill the balloon!

22
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:22,000
Kill the balloon!

23
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Kill the balloon!

24
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Yeah!

25
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Yeah!

26
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,000
Hey.

27
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:38,000
So, they accidentally gave us an extra egg sandwich just to make us feel better.

28
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Hey. So, they accidentally gave us an extra egg sandwich this morning.

29
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,000
Who wants it?

30
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:47,000
Oh, right here. Yes!

31
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:49,000
Allow me to solve your problem, then.

32
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Ellie.

33
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Hmm.

34
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Oh, that is disgusting.

35
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Do you call that a King James breakfast pie?

36
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:02,000
What brings you to town?

37
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Certainly not the Harry Houdini Museum.

38
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:08,000
What a nobody.

39
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
Oh, look, some Hungarian just found their way out of a sack.

40
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Let's build a shrine.

41
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:14,000
No, I've come to work here.

42
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:18,000
What? How could Robert transfer Nellie here after the saber store debacle?

43
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
She stinks of failure.

44
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
The fact that she could show her face around here is an embarrassment.

45
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
I should know. I'm in an identical situation.

46
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Robert did say you'd be joining us. Welcome. I'm Tony.

47
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Oh. What?

48
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,000
I said I'm Tony.

49
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Okay, I made a mistake. I thought it might go unnoticed.

50
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,000
But I'm Toby.

51
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,000
You messed up saying your name?

52
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:43,000
It happens, okay?

53
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
So, let's just find an empty desk for you,

54
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
and I'm sure Robert will be with you as soon as he gets in.

55
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,000
That one looks empty.

56
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
No, it's Andy's office.

57
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,000
Oh, is it?

58
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:57,000
I have one simple philosophy in business.

59
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:00,000
If the seat is open, the job is open.

60
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,000
It's how I came to briefly race a Formula One car.

61
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
The three slowest laps ever recorded.

62
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Another beautiful day in Tallahassee.

63
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:15,000
Good morning, Alonzo.

64
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:17,000
Good morning, Erin.

65
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
How are you? How's your family doing?

66
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,000
This is my house.

67
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
It has five rooms, not including the garage or the roof.

68
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:27,000
It takes me most of the day just to clean it.

69
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:29,000
Oh, I'm a maid now.

70
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Like in downtown Abbey.

71
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:34,000
Did I not mention I only watch PBS now?

72
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,000
Because we don't have cable.

73
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
We have cable.

74
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:41,000
You just have to turn the TV on three and use the other remote.

75
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
This is Irene, the world's best boss,

76
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
slash roommate, slash cantankerous old coot.

77
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:50,000
I taught you cantankerous, and now you use it against me?

78
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:52,000
See, she's given me everything.

79
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:55,000
A job, a house, a new life.

80
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,000
And a suitor.

81
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Erin, are you going to help me study for the TSA exam later?

82
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,000
You said you would.

83
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Yeah, okay.

84
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:06,000
Tallahassee.

85
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,000
Nellie.

86
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,000
Robert.

87
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:14,000
How are you adjusting to life in Scranton so far?

88
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
So far so good.

89
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
The water pressure in the hotel is marvelous.

90
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:24,000
It is astounding what a difference that can make, isn't it?

91
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:28,000
Now, let's find you something fun to do here, shall we?

92
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Oh, I've already found it.

93
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
I am manager.

94
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
A natural next step. It fits like a glove.

95
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
We have a manager.

96
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:39,000
Do you really? Because it is ten.

97
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:41,000
I've been in this chair for an hour,

98
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:44,000
and no other manager has come and sat in my lap.

99
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Excuse me, has anyone seen Andy this morning?

100
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
Oh, yeah, that's weird. He's usually here by now.

101
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Right, guys?

102
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:57,000
Hello?

103
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:59,000
Andy, it's Robert.

104
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Why aren't you at work?

105
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Hey, Robert.

106
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,000
I really wish I could come into work today, but I'm super sick.

107
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:08,000
I don't care. I don't care.

108
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Please come to work immediately.

109
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:19,000
Okay, I'll try to come in, even though I'm really sick with the Florida flu.

110
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
He just hung up on me mid-sentence.

111
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,000
I'm in Florida to get Erin.

112
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,000
As soon as I heard she wasn't coming back to Scranton,

113
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
I jumped straight in my car and drove straight down till I hit the ocean.

114
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:32,000
My heart is my map.

115
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:35,000
Turns out Tallahassee is about 200 miles inland,

116
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
so I overshot a good amount.

117
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:41,000
But still not bad for a heart map, right?

118
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
No.

119
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Thanks a lot, BP.

120
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Not much we can do about this until he gets here.

121
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
Can't you do something about this?

122
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,000
Sometimes the flowers arrange themselves, Jim.

123
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Right.

124
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:03,000
What is going on?

125
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:05,000
And where is Andy?

126
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,000
And what is going on?

127
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:08,000
This is insane.

128
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,000
Has anyone talked to Andy?

129
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,000
He's not returning any calls.

130
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:15,000
I checked his Facebook status, said, pump for Wednesday.

131
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Today's Thursday.

132
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:21,000
I hate to take you to this place, but, Rea, Andy, has anyone checked the morgue?

133
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
Checking the morgue isn't a real thing.

134
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:24,000
That's a real thing.

135
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:25,000
You're a policeman.

136
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:26,000
No, anyone.

137
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
You're just like, hey, can I look around?

138
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:29,000
Anyone?

139
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Yeah, and they have names on everything.

140
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:31,000
I didn't know you were a police officer.

141
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:32,000
Then you go to the graveyard.

142
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:33,000
Then you go to the graveyard.

143
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,000
Okay, okay, okay.

144
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:35,000
Look for a cemetery plot.

145
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:36,000
Guys, shh.

146
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,000
Andy's fine, all right?

147
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,000
Last time he was this late, he just lost track of time

148
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:43,000
watching a Today Show segment on men's shorts, so it's fine.

149
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,000
Well, what's Nellie like?

150
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
She's a classic case of failing upwards.

151
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:49,000
That's how cantaloupe got popular.

152
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,000
I'm gonna text Andy.

153
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Brian, will you put my phone in text mode?

154
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
What's this, then?

155
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,000
Everyone okay?

156
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
Just some casual conversations?

157
00:06:58,000 --> 00:06:59,000
Yeah, exactly.

158
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:04,000
Let's all follow Mama Goose into the meeting room, then, shall we, Ducklings?

159
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:05,000
Nellie.

160
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:07,000
Yes.

161
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,000
Robert.

162
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
Yes.

163
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:16,000
Come on.

164
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
You heard her.

165
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,000
So this is what we're doing now, then?

166
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:23,000
We're just...

167
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,000
So what is going on?

168
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:28,000
That does seem to be the question, doesn't it?

169
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Hey, this is messed up, bro.

170
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,000
Who is this weird lady?

171
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,000
I know.

172
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:36,000
It's a lot.

173
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,000
So who knows what's going on?

174
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:40,000
I don't know.

175
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:42,000
I don't know.

176
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:45,000
So who knows what's going on?

177
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:46,000
Anyone?

178
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,000
You, yes.

179
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
Wait, I am very good at intuiting names.

180
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:52,000
Is it...

181
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:54,000
Chumbo?

182
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:00,000
I think it's a cross between Dumbo and Jumbo.

183
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,000
With a hint of Chubby.

184
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
It's not a name.

185
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,000
Erin, you got a package!

186
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,000
I'm in the bathroom!

187
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:10,000
Where's the postage?

188
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,000
There's no shipping label.

189
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:14,000
Did you wash your hands?

190
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:16,000
Yes.

191
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:20,000
Here I am, sun-sealed, delivered.

192
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:22,000
I'm yours!

193
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
Andy, what are you doing here?

194
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
It's great to see you.

195
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:31,000
I am here to take you back to Scranton.

196
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:35,000
Because I love you and I want to be with you.

197
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,000
Where's the ring?

198
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,000
Where's the ring, Lancelot?

199
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Would you mind if we talked privately for a second?

200
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Sorry, Glenn.

201
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:55,000
Andy, I am so happy to see you, but I'm not coming back with you.

202
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,000
Why won't she go with him?

203
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:59,000
I don't know.

204
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:01,000
Maybe it's because he's not that handsome.

205
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,000
Hey, don't listen.

206
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
Well, this is not what I expected.

207
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:12,000
Especially after driving here all night.

208
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:15,000
I'm sorry. You must be tired.

209
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
No, actually I'm not tired.

210
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:20,000
I had a 12-pack of this energy drink called Up Yours.

211
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:23,000
It has a picture of a hyena giving you the finger on the can.

212
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:25,000
I feel weird.

213
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:27,000
It's just...

214
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,000
Can I stay for lunch?

215
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Oh.

216
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,000
As a friend?

217
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:35,000
Well, I'd have to boil another hot dog.

218
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:37,000
But yes, of course, yes.

219
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
I'm not going to give up that easily.

220
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:40,000
Let me tell you something.

221
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:42,000
If a long drive was all it took to win over a girl,

222
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:46,000
then supermodels would be married to long-haul truckers.

223
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
That's where I keep my spices.

224
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:51,000
Cumin, saffron, paprika.

225
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:54,000
I bought everything you need to make a paella.

226
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:55,000
She means papaya.

227
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,000
I mean paella.

228
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Great. The maid has a visitor.

229
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:03,000
Maybe he'll use my exercise bike too.

230
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
So no one can tell me what's going on.

231
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:08,000
Well, let me illuminate things for you.

232
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:11,000
We are getting to know each other.

233
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:12,000
But why?
